<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[Luke]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-02-28T12:21:19-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-02-28T12:21:19-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4394&amp;p=74812#p74812</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4394&amp;p=74812#p74812"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[NES emulator as a screensaver?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4394&amp;p=74812#p74812"><![CDATA[
I will look at all of the upscaling and graphics effects code again, but I think I have already optimized that code to the best of my abilities.  In the meantime, here are some options you can try to speed things up:<br /><br />- The biggest thing is turning off all of the post-processing effects.  <br /><br />- You can also experiment with GDI/DirectDraw/Direct2D output; I have seen each graphics API perform better than the others on different machines so it might take a little trial and error to find the one that works best for you.  <br /><br />- The faster software upscaler is nearest neighbor.<br /><br />- The movie wall window has an option to restrict the number of unique NES instances running.  Lowering that will almost certainly improve performance, but games may be duplicated to fill out the contents of the wall.<br /><br />Please let me know if you are able to get it running better or if you have any other questions.   <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3699">Luke</a> — Mon Feb 28, 2011 12:21 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
